# Properties

Properties are variables that belong to a class. They represent the state of an object. You declare them with a visibility keyword (`public`, `private`, `protected`) – more on that later.

```php
class Car {
    public $color;
    public $brand;
}
```

You can access them using the object operator `->`:

```php
$myCar = new Car();
$myCar->color = 'red';
echo $myCar->color;
```

# Methods

Methods are functions defined inside a class. They define what the object can do.

```php
class Car {
    public $color;

    public function honk() {
        echo "Beep beep!";
    }
}
```

Call a method using `->` as well:

```php
$myCar->honk();
```

Inside a method, you can access properties using `$this`, which refers to the current object:

```php
public function describe() {
    echo "This car is " . $this->color;
}
```

```php
<?php
class Car {
    public $color;
    public $brand;

    public function setColor($color) {
        $this->color = $color;
    }

    public function getDescription() {
        return "This car is a " . $this->color . " " . $this->brand;
    }
}

$myCar = new Car();
$myCar->brand = 'Toyota';
$myCar->setColor('blue');
echo $myCar->getDescription(); // This car is a blue Toyota
?>
```
